1 and improving the state's economy; and
2 (6) it is in the public interest that the energy authority has the ability to facilitate the planning,
3 development, economic analysis, and coordination of energy generation and electric transmission.
4
5 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Definitions. As used in [sections 1 through 10], unless the context
6 clearly indicates otherwise, the following definitions apply:
7 (1) "Authority" means the energy authority established in [section 4].
8 (2) "Department" means the department of commerce provided for in 2-15-1801.
9
10 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Energy authority -- composition -- allocation. (1) There is an energy
11 authority created to diversify and expand the state's economy by developing and advising in this state the
12 energy production facilities and the electric transmission facilities necessary to produce and transport energy to
13 markets within the state and regionally.
14 (2) The authority is allocated to the department of commerce for administrative purposes only as
15 prescribed in 2-15-121. However, the authority may hire its own executive director, and 2-15-121(2)(d) does not
16 apply.
17 (3) (a) The authority is composed of 14 members appointed by the governor in the same manner
18 as provided in 2-15-124, except as otherwise provided in this section and except that the requirement that at
19 least one member be an attorney does not apply. The authority must be representative of state and local
20 utilities, cooperatives, developers, and stakeholders engaged in the sustainment and development of the state's
21 energy future.
22 (4) (a) Except as provided in subsection (4)(b), appointed members serve staggered terms of 3
23 years.
24 (b) The initial appointments are as follows:
25
26 (i) four members appointed to 1-year terms;
27
28 (ii) four members appointed to 2-year terms; and
- 2 - LC 1484

